# Zeta Kill Chain Oracle — Architecture & Wiring Doctrine (v3)

> **LOCKED SPEC** — this document reflects the v3 Oracle Unified Panel architecture.
> All future oracle work must align with this.

---

## Core Rules (Non-Negotiable)

1. **One oracle brain, many slices.** `/api/v1/oracle/brief` is the only production LLM endpoint. No panel calls Groq directly in production.
2. **`GROQ_API_KEY` lives on the backend only.** `VITE_GROQ_API_KEY` is allowed in `.env.local` for dev only — it must NOT be set in `.env.production` or any Render env var.
3. **Guardrails are universal.** Do NOT override discrete signals. If `layer_3.triggered === false`, you may not say it is firing. Only summarize confluence, highlight contradictions, map to trade implications.
4. **KC is a slice, not a separate pipeline.** `AiBriefingPanel` reads `oracle.sections.kill_chain.summary` as its primary signal, not its own Groq call.

---

## Priority Routing in AiBriefingPanel

```
CLICK (any KC card)
       │
       ▼
PATH 1: unified oracle healthy?
 oracle.risk_level !== 'UNKNOWN'
 && oracle.sections.kill_chain.summary exists
       │ YES → display KC slice  [badge: UNIFIED · NYX — cyan]
       │
       │ NO (oracle/brief not yet deployed or UNKNOWN)
       ▼
PATH 2: POST /api/v1/oracle/analyze (backend)
 body includes kill_chain_snapshot (full KC state)
 GROQ_API_KEY on server; no secret in browser bundle
       │ OK  → display analysis  [badge: KC · GROQ — orange]
       │
       │ FAIL (backend unreachable)
       ▼
PATH 3: direct Groq (dev-only if VITE_GROQ_API_KEY present)
 NEVER in production  [badge: DEV · GROQ — yellow]
       │ FAIL → ORACLE_UPLINK_FAILURE  [badge: OFFLINE — red]
```

The badge in the panel header always shows which path fired.

---

## Kill Chain in the Unified Oracle

When `/api/v1/oracle/brief` is live, `build_oracle_payload()` must include:

```python
"kill_chain": {
    "alert_level":    brief["kill_chain_state"].get("alert_level"),
    "layers_active":  brief["kill_chain_state"].get("layers_active"),
    "confidence_cap": brief["kill_chain_state"].get("confidence_cap"),
    "mismatches":     brief["kill_chain_state"].get("mismatches_count"),
    "narrative":      brief["kill_chain_state"].get("narrative"),
}
```

`oracle.sections.kill_chain.summary` then describes the same KC state the dashboard shows. No divergence.

